    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, the message cut off. You said \"Just like a group of...\"? What were you saying?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Just like a group of **goblins** trying to hoard gold in a single chest! When too many goblins rush to grab the same shiny coin at once, they start bumping into each other, creating a chaotic mess where no one can actually get what they want.\n\nIn your case, those goblins are your database transactions. The `db_transaction_lock_442` is that single chest. When traffic spikes, more goblins (requests) try to enter the chest simultaneously. Some goblins hold the key to the chest while others wait outside, creating a **deadlock** where everyone is stuck waiting for someone else to let go.\n\nThe `state_machine_v2` is the goblin leader who gets confused when the goblins stop moving because they're all arguing over the chest. Instead of just waiting politely, the system throws a **500 error** to stop the chaos, but it feels like a crash to the user.\n\nTo fix this, you need to teach the goblins to be more polite:\n1.  **Shorten their patience**: Set a strict timeout so goblins give up quickly if they can't get the chest, preventing them from holding it forever.\n2.",
